    </div>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer">
          <span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Do you only service turf that Brainard's installed?</span>
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">No. We'll clean and deodorize any artificial turf regardless of who installed it. The enzyme treatment works the same on any turf product — the odor-causing bacteria don't care who laid the turf down.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer">
          <span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Is the treatment safe for my pets?</span>
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Yes. The enzyme-based products we use are non-toxic and pet-safe once the treatment has dried — typically within an hour or two depending on the heat. We'll let you know exactly when it's safe to let pets back on the turf.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer">
          <span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Why not just use antimicrobial infill instead?</span>
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">In Las Cruces, manufactured infill is largely a wasted expense. Airborne sand naturally fills the turf fibers on its own. Once any infill is installed, it compacts hard — like concrete fines — and can't be removed or replaced. Enzyme treatments are repeatable, effective, and don't lock you into a one-time decision you can't undo.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer">
          <span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">How long does the treatment last?</span>
          <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">It depends on pet usage, yard size, and the season. In summer, most yards with one or two dogs stay fresh for about a month. In cooler months, a single treatment can last two to three months. We'll help you find the right schedule for your situation.</div>
      </details>
    </div>
